<font color="#FF0000">GOOD CONVERSATION GUYS!</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 10  0:10:18 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Thanks for sharing brothers.  I wonder were Cook is ?  I was looking forward to his response.  <br><br>
 Paul, my folks pray for me daily too.  It's not that I am a nonreligious person but my parents were and still are Fundamentalist Conservative Baptists.  Can't get any more straight and narrow than that.  I still believe in Christ's teachings, but I don't feel compelled to go to church. So...they worry about me.<br><br>
Tom,  thanks for sharing the story about Chaplain Nichols.  When a person is really touched and then used by God they can make a big difference in other people's lives.  Chaplain Nichols was one of those men from what you say. <br><br>
Welcome back Doc.  I've missed your wisdom. Hope you are feeling much better.  What you stated on how I was raised is a pretty accurate.  In retrospect sounds pretty simplistic I know.  But I believe there was something similar going for most of us who served our country.  Our nation called.  We were raised to be patriots (some in military families where it was expected that each generation would have its own war to fight).  That anyone would even protest against the war was inconceivable.  I don't think it had ever been done before.  But ours were tumultuous times where many standards were being challenged.  You said you never had the need for organized religion, sects or philosophies but you do have codes which you live by.  Did any of them change because of your time in Vietnam?<br><br>
Art, I am fascinated by your journey.  I see a bit of myself in what you are describing.  I sense the presense of a supreme being when I am quiet and willing to listen. It isn't surprizing that I can't hear him when I am doing all the talking.  God, or whatever name we use, that being was never lost, he has been with us all along.  I have faith you will find him.<br><br>

